                <head>195. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>Director of Central Intelligence <persName corresp="#p_DAW1">Allen
                        Dulles</persName> prepared a paper for a review of national security policy
                    then underway on November 18, 1954. <persName corresp="#p_DAW1"
                        >Dulles</persName> reviewed the evolving dynamics of the superpower
                    competition, predicting that, over the next few years, the Soviet Union would
                    become a more formidable competitor with the West in all regions of the world.
                    To respond to this growing competition (which <persName corresp="#p_DAW1"
                        >Dulles</persName> believed would remain primarily diplomatic, economic, and
                    cultural, and was not likely to result in a ground war), <persName
                        corresp="#p_DAW1">Dulles</persName> noted that the United States needed “to
                    employ in a closely coordinated fashion all the cold war weapons at its
                    disposal.” To do so, the government required “the decisive coordination of
                    political, military, economic and covert actions.” The text is in <ref
                        target="frus1952-54v02p1#pg_776">
                        <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1952–1954, volume II, Part 1,
                        pages 776</ref>–<ref target="frus1952-54v02p1#pg_781">781</ref>.</p>
            </div>
